  {
    "id": "bank-a-q014",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "magnetic-tape",
    "stem": "Magnetic tape is not practical for applications where data must be quickly recalled because tape is __________.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "A random-access medium",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "A sequential-access medium",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "A read-only medium",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "An expensive storage medium",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "Tape is a sequential-access medium: to reach a record the drive must physically wind past everything stored before it, so access time depends on position and can be minutes. A disk is random access and can seek straight to the data, which is why tape is used for backup and archive, not for data that must be recalled quickly.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 14
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "e3b06fb5ca02e34c5476166f8b7b9d8a78a0d2d0"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q015",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "core-memory",
    "stem": "What is the main advantage of magnetic core memory over semiconductor RAM memory?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "More compact and smaller",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "More economical",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "A bit does not have to write after reading",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Non-volatile",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "D"
    ],
    "explanation": "Magnetic core memory stores each bit as the magnetisation direction of a ferrite ring, which persists with no power, so it is non-volatile, unlike semiconductor RAM. The other options are wrong in the opposite direction: core is bulkier, more expensive, and its reads are destructive, so a bit does have to be written back after being read.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 15
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [
      "legacy"
    ],
    "dedupeHash": "e7199fdafd8d4e013404128a28c2d9a31d3e8fbf"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q016",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "hard-disk",
    "stem": "Hard disc drives are considered.........storage-",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Flash",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Non-volatile",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Temporary",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Non-permanent",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "E",
        "text": "None of these",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "A hard disk stores bits as magnetised regions on a platter, and magnetisation survives power off, so an HDD is non-volatile storage. 'Flash' is the trap: flash is also non-volatile, but it is the semiconductor technology used in SSDs and USB sticks, not in a magnetic hard disc drive.",
    "source": {
